SIMPLE: impulse
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Impulse
<hw>Im"pulse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>impulsus</ets>, fr. <ets>impellere</ets>. See
<er>Impel</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of impelling, or driving onward with sudden
force; impulsion; especially, force so communicated as to produced
motion suddenly, or immediately.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All spontaneous animal motion is performed by mechanical
<qex>impulse</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>S. Clarke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The effect of an impelling force; motion produced by
a sudden or momentary force.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>The action of a force during a
very small interval of time; the effect of such action; <as>as, the
<ex>impulse</ex> of a sudden blow upon a hard elastic
body</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A mental force which simply and directly urges to
action; hasty inclination; sudden motive; momentary or transient
influence of appetite or passion; propension; incitement; <as>as, a man
of good <ex>impulses</ex>; passion often gives a violent
<ex>impulse</ex> to the will; to buy something on
<ex>impulse</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>These were my natural <qex>impulses</qex> for the undertaking.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Force; incentive; influence; motive; feeling;
incitement; instigation.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impulse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Impulse
<hw>Im*pulse"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Impel</er>.]</ety> <def>To impel; to incite.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>impulse-buy</ent>⟦br⟧
